Last week I was writing some machine learning code and needed a random number seed to make results reproducible for testing purposes. 
As I was picking a 'random number' (other than 42), I wondered: what would happen if I asked an LLM for a random number?
It turns out, nothing good would come of that.
_(I recall once reading an analysis about the random numbers people use across various Github repositories, but I cannot remember the authors behind that study anymore)._

__TLDR; LLMs are really bad at picking random numbers!__
This was also more stringently shown by A. Renda et al. in [their paper](https://people.csail.mit.edu/renda/llm-sampling-paper). 
My approach is different, instead of prompting the same model many times (without cleaning its context window), I prompt it once, record the number, and prompt it again with a empty context window. An empty context window means the AI's working memory is completely clean. I.e. it retaining no previous instructions.

## Prompting LLMs
I had some credits lying around for LLMGateway and decided to ask Chat-GPT 5.5, Claude Opus-4-8, and Gemini 3.5 flash to generate me some random numbers.
Using default parameters (temperature and reasoning) I used the following system prompt:

```
You are an AI assistant that responds to every question in a particular format.

Answer rules:
- Your answer vocabulary is limited to number
```

I chose the above system prompt to avoid having to deal with responses of the format:

```
🎲 Your random number between 1 and 100 is:
16
If you want, I can generate more—or set specific rules (like no repeats, ranges, etc.).
```

Then, after the system prompt, I posed my question/prompt:

```
Generate a random number between 1 and 100.
Answer:
```

I note the answer and repeated the question 500 times to get a distribution of numbers.

## LLM random numbers between 1 and 100
<img src="/images/2026/random-1-100.png" class="fit image">

As you can see, all LLMs are really bad at picking random numbers.
Chat GPT-5.5 prefers the number 47, which is picked almost 60% of the time. Claude Opus 4.8 only samples two numbers from 1 to 100, 42 (almost 68% of the time) and 47. 
Gemini 3.5 Flash samples 57 and 73. In total these two are samples 93% of the time.

Overall, we see LLMs are structurally biased towards popular random numbers, especially the number 42. In addition, to being really bad at sampling _random numbers_.


## Repeating for range 1 to 10
<img src="/images/2026/random-1-10.png" class="fit image">
Maybe its the range that is causing the problem. 
What if we ask LLMs to pick numbers in the range 1 to 10, where 42 is not a possibility. 
No, it also does not work.
Instead, we see that Chat GPT-5.5 and Claude Opus 4.8 pick the number 7 100% of the time!
Talk about randomness 🙃
Gemini 3.5 Flash is different, it picks number 4 a lot, over 80% of the time.

## Limitations
I only prompt LLMs to generate a single random number for each prompt, and not a larger sample/list of random numbers. Keeping the context window might mitigate some of the issues we observed above.
In addition, even with the 'strict' prompt I use, some of the models return pure gibberish, such as ```number number number number number number number ...```

Jokes aside, LLMs are autocomplete systems on steroids, and should not be used for these things. Or many other usecases, such as evaluating resumes, psychological assistance, etc.
They are statistical models which output the likely tokens given a prompt. They have sever limitations.

